HEADWORD: Impenitence
<hw>Im*pen"i*tence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>impenitentia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>imp⟦eacute⟧nitence</ets>.]</ety>
<def>The condition of being impenitent; failure or refusal to repent;
hardness of heart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He will advance from one degree of wickedness and
<qex>impenitence</qex> to another.</q> <rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impenitency</ent>⟦br⟧
